"     Written by the doctors and editors at UpToDate",
"    </a>",
"    <div id=\"topicText\">",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H396302540\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What is pneumonia?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Pneumonia is an infection of the lungs that causes coughing, fever, and trouble breathing (",
"      <a class=\"graphic graphic_figure graphicRef55943 \" href=\"mobipreview.htm?10/3/10294\">",
"       figure 1",
"      </a>",
"      ). It is a serious illness, especially in young children, people older than 65, and people with other health problems. Pneumonia is usually caused by bacteria but can also be caused by viruses or other germs.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H396302491\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What are the symptoms of pneumonia?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Common symptoms include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Cough",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Fever",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Trouble breathing",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Pain when you take a deep breath",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        A fast heartbeat",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Shaking chills",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      When people with pneumonia cough, they often cough up phlegm or mucus.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H396302498\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Should I see a doctor or nurse if I think I have pneumonia?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Yes, see a doctor or nurse as soon as possible.",
"      <strong>",
"      </strong>",
"      Pneumonia can be mild. But it can also be very serious, especially if you do not get it treated right away. See your doctor or nurse if:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Your cough keeps getting worse",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        You start having trouble breathing when doing everyday tasks or when resting",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        You have a fever of 102&deg;F (or 38.8&deg;C) or higher",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        You have chest pain when you breathe in",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        You feel suddenly worse after getting better from a cold or the flu",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      If your doctor or nurse thinks you might have pneumonia, he or she will probably take an x-ray of your chest. Taking a chest x-ray is the best way to tell if you have pneumonia.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H396302505\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       How is pneumonia treated?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Pneumonia that is caused by bacteria is treated with antibiotics. These medicines kill the germs that cause pneumonia. Most people can take antibiotic pills at home, but some people need to be treated in the hospital. Make sure to take all of your antibiotics, even if you feel better before you finish them!",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H396302512\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       How soon will I feel better?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;You should start to feel better 3 to 5 days after you start taking antibiotics. Most people can get back to their normal routine within a week of starting treatment. Even so, you might feel tired or have a cough for up to a month after you get treated.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H396302519\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       How should I take care of myself until I recover?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Get lots of rest and drink lots of fluids. See your doctor or nurse 4 to 6 weeks after you get better. He or she will want to make sure everything is back to normal.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H396302526\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What can I do to keep from getting pneumonia again?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;You can wash your hands often with soap and water, or use alcohol hand rubs. Doing so will help protect you from germs.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      There is also a vaccine against the most common type of bacterial pneumonia. But the vaccine is not for everyone. Ask your doctor if it is right for you. Most people should also get a flu vaccine every year.",
"     </p>",
